<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,318,386,412]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[335,506,386,411]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xerxes">
<emphasis box="[335,506,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Ocypus xerxes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares most of the character states with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[991,1116,386,412]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elpenor">
<emphasis box="[991,1012,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1028,1116,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">elpenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from it mainly by the differently shaped aedoeagus and tergite 10 of the female genital segment, and by a few additional characters, as given in the description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,506,532]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Description</emphasis>
. Male. Sternite 8 with medioapical emargination slightly narrower and less deep. Sternite 9 of genital segment similar, but with medioapical emargination narrower, less deep, obtusely angular (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 136–142" captionStartId="61.[151,269,1798,1822]" captionTargetBox="[268,1320,202,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-60@61.[264,1323,194,1774]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 136–142. Details of Ocypus elpenor (136–139) and O. xerxes (140–142). 136—aedoeagus, ventral view; 137—underside of paramere; 138—underside of apical portion of paramere; 139—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 140—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 141—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 142—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
). Tergite 10 similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[549,673,586,612]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elpenor">
<emphasis box="[549,570,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[585,673,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">elpenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but more densely setose at apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[1182,1284,586,612]" captionStart="FIGURES 136–142" captionStartId="61.[151,269,1798,1822]" captionTargetBox="[268,1320,202,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-60@61.[264,1323,194,1774]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 136–142. Details of Ocypus elpenor (136–139) and O. xerxes (140–142). 136—aedoeagus, ventral view; 137—underside of paramere; 138—underside of apical portion of paramere; 139—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 140—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 141—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 142—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 141</figureCitation>
). Aedoeagus (
<figureCitation box="[159,329,626,652]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 136–142" captionStart-1="FIGURES 143–150" captionStartId-0="61.[151,269,1798,1822]" captionStartId-1="62.[151,269,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox-0="[268,1320,202,1766]" captionTargetBox-1="[265,1318,213,1721]" captionTargetId-0="figure-60@61.[264,1323,194,1774]" captionTargetId-1="figure-73@62.[264,1323,194,1728]" captionTargetPageId-0="61" captionTargetPageId-1="62" captionText-0="FIGURES 136–142. Details of Ocypus elpenor (136–139) and O. xerxes (140–142). 136—aedoeagus, ventral view; 137—underside of paramere; 138—underside of apical portion of paramere; 139—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 140—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 141—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 142—aedoeagus, ventral view." captionText-1="FIGURES 143–150. Details of Ocypus xerxes (143–146) and O. pammenes (147–150). 143—apical portion of median lobe, ventral view, paramere removed; 144—underside of paramere; 145, 150—underside of apical portion of paramere; 146—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 147—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 148—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 149—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Figs. 142–144</figureCitation>
) built in a similar way as that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[714,838,626,652]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elpenor">
<emphasis box="[714,735,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[750,838,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">elpenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but apical portion of median lobe almost symmetrical, apex arcuate (
<figureCitation box="[385,489,666,692]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–150" captionStartId="62.[151,269,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox="[265,1318,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-73@62.[264,1323,194,1728]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 143–150. Details of Ocypus xerxes (143–146) and O. pammenes (147–150). 143—apical portion of median lobe, ventral view, paramere removed; 144—underside of paramere; 145, 150—underside of apical portion of paramere; 146—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 147—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 148—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 149—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 143</figureCitation>
); paramere similar, but apical portion narrower, markedly more curved mediad, apex of paramere not reaching apex of median lobe; right margin of paramere, when paramere removed from median lobe and viewed with underside up, appearing obtusely angulate (
<figureCitation box="[1012,1172,746,772]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–150" captionStartId="62.[151,269,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox="[265,1318,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-73@62.[264,1323,194,1728]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 143–150. Details of Ocypus xerxes (143–146) and O. pammenes (147–150). 143—apical portion of median lobe, ventral view, paramere removed; 144—underside of paramere; 145, 150—underside of apical portion of paramere; 146—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 147—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 148—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 149—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 144, 145</figureCitation>
); sensory peg setae on underside of paramere situated differently, apical setae reduced to one seta at left margin below apex (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 143–150" captionStartId="62.[151,269,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox="[265,1318,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-73@62.[264,1323,194,1728]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 143–150. Details of Ocypus xerxes (143–146) and O. pammenes (147–150). 143—apical portion of median lobe, ventral view, paramere removed; 144—underside of paramere; 145, 150—underside of apical portion of paramere; 146—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 147—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 148—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 149—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 145</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
Female. Tergite 10 of genital segment similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[855,980,866,892]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elpenor">
<emphasis box="[855,876,866,891]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[892,980,866,891]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">elpenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but wider and of different shape (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 143–150" captionStartId="62.[151,269,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox="[265,1318,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-73@62.[264,1323,194,1728]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 143–150. Details of Ocypus xerxes (143–146) and O. pammenes (147–150). 143—apical portion of median lobe, ventral view, paramere removed; 144—underside of paramere; 145, 150—underside of apical portion of paramere; 146—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 147—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 148—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 149—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 146</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" box="[198,466,946,972]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Length 15.0–18.0 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,328,986,1012]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Bionomics</emphasis>
. The specimens of the original series were taken from pitfall traps, but no details are known about the habitat the traps were set in.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" box="[198,1401,1066,1092]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,523,1066,1092]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Geographical distribution</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[538,708,1066,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xerxes">
<emphasis box="[538,708,1066,1091]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Ocypus xerxes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<materialsCitation box="[715,1397,1066,1092]" location="Sichuan" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Sichuan">
is at present known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1116,1166,1066,1092]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingRegion box="[1299,1397,1066,1092]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,536,1106,1132]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Recognition and comments</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[549,719,1107,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xerxes">
<emphasis box="[549,719,1107,1132]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Ocypus xerxes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be positively distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[1166,1290,1106,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Ocypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elpenor">
<emphasis box="[1166,1187,1107,1132]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1201,1290,1107,1132]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">elpenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the characteristically shaped aedoeagus, in combination with the shape of tergite 10 of the female genital segment (
<figureCitation box="[159,272,1186,1212]" captionStart="FIGURES 136–142" captionStartId="61.[151,269,1798,1822]" captionTargetBox="[268,1320,202,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-60@61.[264,1323,194,1774]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 136–142. Details of Ocypus elpenor (136–139) and O. xerxes (140–142). 136—aedoeagus, ventral view; 137—underside of paramere; 138—underside of apical portion of paramere; 139—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 140—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 141—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 142—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Figs. 139</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[284,332,1186,1212]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–150" captionStartId="62.[151,269,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox="[265,1318,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-73@62.[264,1323,194,1728]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 143–150. Details of Ocypus xerxes (143–146) and O. pammenes (147–150). 143—apical portion of median lobe, ventral view, paramere removed; 144—underside of paramere; 145, 150—underside of apical portion of paramere; 146—tergite 10 of female genital segment; 147—sternite 9 of male genital segment; 148—tergite 10 of male genital segment; 149—aedoeagus, ventral view." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">146</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Several specimens of the original series are in poor shape (missing appendages, broken body parts), obviously as a result of prolonged exposure to the fluids in the pitfall traps.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,1436,1306,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,266,1332]" box="[198,1436,1306,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,331,1306,1332]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet is the name of 
<emphasis box="[752,831,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Xerxes</emphasis>
